Rating: 3
With so many 4 fork ratings I just had to choose this recipe over the other banana bread recipes. I made it exactly as written except I made two loaves and 12 muffins from the batter because I always seem to over brown the tops in order to get the middles to bake properly; it was perfect judgement. The loaves baked in one hour. I found the bread so sweet that the tops of the muffins actually sugar-crisped - glassy sweet crunch. I'll use at least half the sugar next time. I will also follow other reviewer's lead and try 1/2 oil and 1/2 applesauce, which a few said was a delicious way to cut the fat and calories for no loss of taste/texture.

Rating: 4
This is the best banana bread I have ever had. Easy to prepare and has perfect moistness and texture. I could not find creme fraiche, so I used sour cream.

Rating: 4
This is a great, sweet banana bread recipe. I like to use whole grains, so I substituted in 1 c King Arthur white whole wheat flour plus 1 c barley flour for two of the cups of white flour, and added an extra 1/2 tsp of baking soda. I also increased the oil to 1 1/4 cup and use 1/2 cup of sour cream instead of the 1/4 cup of creme fraiche. Delicious!

Rating: 4
This is the perfect, basic banana bread recipe. I substituted some whole wheat flour to give it a little more substance and it was great. I also discovered a cool trick: a potato ricer mashes bananas beautifully! And it is so much fun to do.

Rating: 4
This is a delicious recipe -- very moist. Be careful of cooking times. I've made this recipe at least a dozen times and each time the baking time has been different. Also make sure the banana is well mashed -- I wouldn't do "coarse" as the recipe calls for -- you'll have sections of uncooked bread.

