Rating: 3
I decided to try this with modifications to make it more healthful. I've tried "lowfat" banana bread recipes and have always been disappointed, but this translated very well and I will make my own version of this again. My substitutions may be too much for some, but I did like it... I used applesauce in place of oil, whole wheat flour instead of white (it was quite dense, so maybe 50-50 would be good for most), egg substitute, splenda sweetener and almonds instead of walnuts. Very good -- much, much better than the recipes that I've tried that are designed to be lowfat or "healthy."

Rating: 2
After buying 25 bananas to give out to the monkeys at a safari park, and then deciding not to go, I was searching for a recipe that used lots of the fruit. This called for 6 but we actually needed 7 to make 3 cups of mush. Yay! The bread it produces is good -- so moist it could really qualify as a cake. I took one cook's suggestion; since I hate finding walnuts in baked goods, I added a generous handful of chopped macadamias. They didn't add as luxurious a flavor sensation as expected -- thus, while I wouldn't necessarily suggest adding them, I'm sure they tasted better than the alternative. But one question remains about ripe bananas: Is there any such thing as TOO ripe? Some of the bananas I used were literally falling apart. Others I mashed were simply getting soft. The result was sweet and banana-y, so I guess it doesn't matter much. (But I did find myself wondering whether it was healthy to eat something so funky.)

